															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/novaedearx" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1310897); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1310897&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610163881" alt="NovaeDeArx" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1310897)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/novaedearx" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1310897); return false;" >NovaeDeArx</a></span> <span class="odate time_1341809764 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">09 Jul 2012 04:56</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1502741">
									

<p>Thanks! I really liked the idea of the Destroyers from SCP-1050, and this tale is the result of trying to figure out a way to make them more menacing than most of the stuff the Foundation comes across.</p>
<p>In a way, it's sort of meta. The Destroyers are sort of the &quot;cancer&quot; that often inflicts boards like SCP Wiki; the magic sometimes just is gone, and what's left is just a pale, dead imitation of what used to be.</p>
<p>Not to say that SCP Wiki is dying! (I love this place, and they have excellent quality control.) I've just seen good writing boards die from their own success, and this is sort of a piece about that.</p>

							</div>

								
					
